    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="231"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7180</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 3643</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-22">June 22,
                            1935</date>.<lb/>[Received July 13.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to enclose a copy of a
                    memorandum of a conversation<note n="99" xml:id="d231fn99">Not printed.</note>
                    which I had on June 18, 1935, with Mr. Edward Lepin, Military Attaché of the
                    Soviet Embassy, during which he expressed the opinion that the five northern
                    provinces would be divested before the end of the year of any authority of
                    Nanking; that the Japanese had missed their opportunity in 1932 with regard to
                    Russia; and that, if Russia were forced to fight, she would fight on foreign
                    soil. I gathered the impression from his statements that it was his opinion
                    that, if territory lost by China to the Japanese fell to Russia as a result of a
                    Russo-Japanese war, it could not be argued that Soviet Russia was therefore
                    either politically ambitious or acquisitive.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson Trusler Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
